# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acme-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The **Automatic Certificate Management Environment** (**ACME**) protocol is a communications protocol for automating interactions between certificate authorities and their users' servers, allowing the automated deployment of public key infrastructure at very low cost.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] It was designed by the Internet Security Research Group (ISRG) for their Let's Encrypt service.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The protocol, based on passing JSON-formatted messages over HTTPS, has been published as an Internet Standard in RFC 8555 by its own chartered IETF working group.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An automated certificate management protocol was being developed simultaneously by a team led by Alex Halderman at the University of Michigan and by Peter Eckersley at the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), and another team at Mozilla Corporation led by Josh Aas and Eric Rescorla.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Upon learning of each other's existence, the two teams joined to create the Internet Security Research Group (ISRG) in May 2013, a public-benefit non-profit corporation, of which Aas became director.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ISRG continued to develop the ACME protocol for use in their Let's Encrypt certificate authority (CA), with the goal of creating a free, open, secure and private internet, as well as their CA softwares Boulder and Certbot.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The aims of the ACME protocol were to lower the cost of publicly trusted TLS certificates and eliminate the complexity and error-prone nature of installing new certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] A 2013 study co-authored by Halderman found that, on the internet, only 45% of TLS certificates were correctly configured, and about 20% failed to be replaced before their expiration.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The Let's Encrypt certificate authority, the first to support ACME, was opened to the public in December 2015 using the still proprietary protocol referred to as 'ACMEv1'.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] This version was given for public standardization to a newly created ACME working group of the Internet Engineering Task Force under the Internet Society in February 2015.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ACME protocol continues to receive published extensions into 2026.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ACME protocol functions from the server (CA) point of view by assigning to each client an ACME account, bound to a URI on the server.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An account is created by the client querying the server's directory URI, after which the server responds with additional informational endpoints along with the CA's terms of service agreement.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An ACME account is created after the client agrees to the terms by setting the relevant reply field to true.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The client then obtains pre-authorization from the server, ensuring the forthcoming certificate will meet the server's requirements, by sending a subset of the certificate's fields.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The server then replies with an 'order object' URL.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] This packet contains a list of authorization methods supported by the server which ensure the client is in possession of the subject of the potential certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The client downloads an authorization token from the URL(s) indicated in the response and makes this token available, e.g. by creating a DNS record containing it or opening an HTTP endpoint responding with it.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] After the authorization token has been made available at the address of the desired certificate's subject, the client notifies the server that it is prepared for validation which is carried out by the server in accessing the authorization token.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Once the authorization is complete the client sends a certificate signing request (RFC 2986) which contains the certificate to be signed, resulting in an updated order object containing the decision of the CA.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] If the request was valid, the CA has signed the client's certificate and the client may download it at the returned URL.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Functionality also exists for certificate revocation, account deletion, and other forms of authentication.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ISRG provides free and open-source reference implementations for ACME: certbot is a Python-based implementation of server certificate management software using the ACME protocol, and *boulder* is a certificate authority implementation, written in Go.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Client implementations are available for Rust in the `acme-client` and `instant_acme` crates.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Since 2015 a large variety of client options have appeared for all operating systems.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Web servers like Caddy, Traefik Proxy, Nginx (starting in August, 2025), and Apache HTTP Server (2.4.30 and later) have built in support for automatically acquiring a TLS certificate using the ACME protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] API v1 specification was published on April 12, 2016.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] It supports issuing certificates for fully-qualified domain names, such as `example.com` or `cluster.example.com`, but not wildcards like `*.example.com`.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Let's Encrypt turned off API v1 support on 1 June 2021.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] API v2 was released March 13, 2018 after being pushed back several times.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] ACME v2 is not backwards compatible with v1.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Version 2 supports wildcard domains, such as `*.example.com`, allowing for many subdomains to have trusted TLS, e.g.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] `https://cluster01.example.com`, `https://cluster02.example.com`, `https://example.com`, on private networks under a single domain using a single shared "wildcard" certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/automatic-certificate-management-environment] A major new requirement in v2 is that requests for wildcard certificates require the modification of a Domain Name Service TXT record, verifying control over the domain.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In cryptography, a **certificate authority** or **certification authority** (**CA**) is an entity that stores, signs, and issues digital certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made about the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A CA acts as a trusted third party—trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The format of these certificates is specified by the X.509 or EMV standard.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] One particularly common use for certificate authorities is to sign certificates used in HTTPS, the secure browsing protocol for the World Wide Web.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Another common use is in issuing identity cards by national governments for use in electronically signing documents.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Trusted certificates can be used to create secure connections to a server via the Internet.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A certificate is essential in order to circumvent a malicious party which happens to be on the route to a target server which acts as if it were the target.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Such a scenario is commonly referred to as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The client uses the CA certificate to authenticate the CA signature on the server certificate, as part of the authorizations before launching a secure connection.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Usually, client software—for example, browsers—include a set of trusted CA certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This makes sense, as many users need to trust their client software.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A malicious or compromised client can skip any security check and still fool its users into believing otherwise.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The clients of a CA are server supervisors who call for a certificate that their servers will bestow to users.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Commercial CAs charge money to issue certificates, and their customers anticipate the CA's certificate to be contained within the majority of web browsers, so that safe connections to the certified servers work efficiently out-of-the-box.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The quantity of web browsers, other devices, and applications which trust a particular certificate authority is referred to as ubiquity.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Mozilla, which is a non-profit business, issues several commercial CA certificates with its products.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] While Mozilla developed their own policy, the CA/Browser Forum developed similar guidelines for CA trust.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A single CA certificate may be shared among multiple CAs or their resellers.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A *root* CA certificate may be the base to issue multiple *intermediate* CA certificates with varying validation requirements.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In addition to commercial CAs, some non-profits issue publicly-trusted digital certificates without charge, for example Let's Encrypt.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Some large cloud computing and web hosting companies are also publicly-trusted CAs and issue certificates to services hosted on their infrastructure, for example IBM Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Large organizations or government bodies may have their own PKIs (public key infrastructure), each containing their own CAs.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Any site using self-signed certificates acts as its own CA.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Each payment card presents along with its card data also the Card Issuer Certificate to the POS.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The Issuer Certificate is signed by EMV CA Certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The POS retrieves the public key of EMV CA from its storage, validates the Issuer Certificate and authenticity of the payment card before sending the payment request to the payment scheme.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Browsers and other clients of sorts characteristically allow users to add or do away with CA certificates at will.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] While server certificates regularly last for a relatively short period, CA certificates are further extended, so, for repeatedly visited servers, it is less error-prone importing and trusting the CA issued, rather than confirm a security exemption each time the server's certificate is renewed.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Less often, trustworthy certificates are used for encrypting or signing messages.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] CAs dispense end-user certificates too, which can be used with S/MIME.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] However, encryption entails the receiver's public key and, since authors and receivers of encrypted messages, apparently, know one another, the usefulness of a trusted third party remains confined to the signature verification of messages sent to public mailing lists.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Worldwide, the certificate authority business is fragmented, with national or regional providers dominating their home market.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This is because many uses of digital certificates, such as for legally binding digital signatures, are linked to local law, regulations, and accreditation schemes for certificate authorities.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] However, the market for globally trusted TLS/SSL server certificates is largely held by a small number of multinational companies.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This market has significant barriers to entry due to the technical requirements.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] While not legally required, new providers may choose to undergo annual security audits (such as WebTrust for certificate authorities in North America and ETSI in Europe) to be included as a trusted root by a web browser or operating system.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] As of 24 August 2020, 147 root certificates, representing 52 organizations, are trusted in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, 168 root certificates, representing 60 organizations, are trusted by macOS, and 255 root certificates, representing 101 organizations, are trusted by Microsoft Windows.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] As of Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean), Android currently contains over 100 CAs that are updated with each release.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Let's Encrypt is operated by the newly formed Internet Security Research Group, a California nonprofit recognized as federally tax-exempt.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] As of July 2024 the survey company W3Techs, which collects statistics on certificate authority usage among the Alexa top 10 million and the Tranco top 1 million websites, lists the five largest authorities by absolute usage share as below.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The commercial CAs that issue the bulk of certificates for HTTPS servers typically use a technique called "domain validation" to authenticate the recipient of the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The techniques used for domain validation vary between CAs, but in general domain validation techniques are meant to prove that the certificate applicant controls a given domain name, not any information about the applicant's identity.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Many Certificate Authorities also offer Extended Validation (EV) certificates as a more rigorous alternative to domain validated certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Extended validation is intended to verify not only control of a domain name, but additional identity information to be included in the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Some browsers display this additional identity information in a green box in the URL bar.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Domain validation suffers from certain structural security limitations.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In particular, it is always vulnerable to attacks that allow an adversary to observe the domain validation probes that CAs send.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] These can include attacks against the DNS, TCP, or BGP protocols (which lack the cryptographic protections of TLS/SSL), or the compromise of routers.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Such attacks are possible either on the network near a CA, or near the victim domain itself.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] One of the most common domain validation techniques involves sending an email containing an authentication token or link to an email address that is likely to be administratively responsible for the domain.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This could be the technical contact email address listed in the domain's WHOIS entry, or an administrative email like admin@, administrator@, webmaster@, hostmaster@ or postmaster@ the domain.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Some Certificate Authorities may accept confirmation using root@, info@, or support@ in the domain.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The theory behind domain validation is that only the legitimate owner of a domain would be able to read emails sent to these administrative addresses.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Domain validation implementations have sometimes been a source of security vulnerabilities.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In one instance, security researchers showed that attackers could obtain certificates for webmail sites because a CA was willing to use an email address like ssladmin@domain.com for domain.com, but not all webmail systems had reserved the "ssladmin" username to prevent attackers from registering it.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Prior to 2011, there was no standard list of email addresses that could be used for domain validation, so it was not clear to email administrators which addresses needed to be reserved.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The first version of the CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements, adopted November 2011, specified a list of such addresses.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This allowed mail hosts to reserve those addresses for administrative use, though such precautions are still not universal.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In January 2015, a Finnish man registered the username "hostmaster" at the Finnish version of Microsoft Live and was able to obtain a domain-validated certificate for live.fi, despite not being the owner of the domain name.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A CA issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The matching private key is not made available publicly, but kept secret by the end user who generated the key pair.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The certificate is also a confirmation or validation by the CA that the public key contained in the certificate belongs to the person, organization, server or other entity noted in the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A CA's obligation in such schemes is to verify an applicant's credentials, so that users and relying parties can trust the information in the issued certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] CAs use a variety of standards and tests to do so.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In essence, the certificate authority is responsible for saying "yes, this person is who they say they are, and we, the CA, certify that".
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] If the user trusts the CA and can verify the CA's signature, then they can also assume that a certain public key does indeed belong to whoever is identified in the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Public-key cryptography can be used to encrypt data communicated between two parties.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This can typically happen when a user logs on to any site that implements the HTTP Secure protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In this example let us suppose that the user logs on to their bank's homepage www.bank.example to do online banking.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] When the user opens www.bank.example homepage, they receive a public key along with all the data that their web-browser displays.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The rest of the communication then proceeds using the new (disposable) symmetric key, so when the user enters some information to the bank's page and submits the page (sends the information back to the bank) then the data the user has entered to the page will be encrypted by their web browser.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Therefore, even if someone can access the (encrypted) data that was communicated from the user to www.bank.example, such eavesdropper cannot read or decipher it.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This mechanism is only safe if the user can be sure that it is the bank that they see in their web browser.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] If the user types in www.bank.example, but their communication is hijacked and a fake website (that pretends to be the bank website) sends the page information back to the user's browser, the fake web-page can send a fake public key to the user (for which the fake site owns a matching private key).
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The user will fill the form with their personal data and will submit the page.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The fake web-page will then get access to the user's data.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This is what the certificate authority mechanism is intended to prevent.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A certificate authority (CA) is an organization that stores public keys and their owners, and every party in a communication trusts this organization (and knows its public key).
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] When the user's web browser receives the public key from www.bank.example it also receives a digital signature of the key (with some more information, in a so-called X.509 certificate).
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The browser already possesses the public key of the CA and consequently can verify the signature, trust the certificate and the public key in it: since www.bank.example uses a public key that the certification authority certifies, a fake www.bank.example can only use the same public key.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Since the fake www.bank.example does not know the corresponding private key, it cannot create the signature needed to verify its authenticity.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] It is difficult to assure correctness of match between data and entity when the data are presented to the CA (perhaps over an electronic network), and when the credentials of the person/company/program asking for a certificate are likewise presented.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This is why commercial CAs often use a combination of authentication techniques including leveraging government bureaus, the payment infrastructure, third parties' databases and services, and custom heuristics.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In some enterprise systems, local forms of authentication such as Kerberos can be used to obtain a certificate which can in turn be used by external relying parties.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Notaries are required in some cases to personally know the party whose signature is being notarized; this is a higher standard than is reached by many CAs.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] 2. a contract relating to such transaction may not be denied legal effect, validity or enforceability solely because an electronic signature or electronic record was used in its formation.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Despite the security measures undertaken to correctly verify the identities of people and companies, there is a risk of a single CA issuing a bogus certificate to an imposter.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] It is also possible to register individuals and companies with the same or very similar names, which may lead to confusion.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] To minimize this hazard, the *certificate transparency* initiative proposes auditing all certificates in a public unforgeable log, which could help in the prevention of phishing.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In large-scale deployments, Alice may not be familiar with Bob's certificate authority (perhaps they each have a different CA server), so Bob's certificate may also include his CA's public key signed by a different CA2, which is presumably recognizable by Alice.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This process typically leads to a hierarchy or mesh of CAs and CA certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Revocation is performed by the issuing CA, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The CA/Browser Forum publishes the Baseline Requirements, a list of policies and technical requirements for CAs to follow.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] These are a requirement for inclusion in the certificate stores of Firefox and Safari.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] On April 14, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum passed a ballot to reduce SSL/TLS certificates to 47 day maximum term by March 15, 2029.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] If the CA can be subverted, then the security of the entire system is lost, potentially subverting all the entities that trust the compromised CA.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] For example, suppose an attacker, Eve, manages to get a CA to issue to her a certificate that claims to represent Alice.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] That is, the certificate would publicly state that it represents Alice, and might include other information about Alice.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Some of the information about Alice, such as her employer name, might be true, increasing the certificate's credibility.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Eve, however, would have the all-important private key associated with the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Eve could then use the certificate to send a digitally signed email to Bob, tricking Bob into believing that the email was from Alice.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Bob might even respond with encrypted email, believing that it could only be read by Alice, when Eve is actually able to decrypt it using the private key.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] A notable case of CA subversion like this occurred in 2001, when the certificate authority VeriSign issued two certificates to a person claiming to represent Microsoft.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The certificates have the name "Microsoft Corporation", so they could be used to spoof someone into believing that updates to Microsoft software came from Microsoft when they actually did not.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Microsoft and VeriSign took steps to limit the impact of the problem.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In 2008, Comodo reseller Certstar sold a certificate for mozilla.com to Eddy Nigg, who had no authority to represent Mozilla.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In 2011 fraudulent certificates were obtained from Comodo and DigiNotar, allegedly by Iranian hackers.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] There is evidence that the fraudulent DigiNotar certificates were used in a man-in-the-middle attack in Iran.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In 2012, it became known that Trustwave issued a subordinate root certificate that was used for transparent traffic management (man-in-the-middle) which effectively permitted an enterprise to sniff SSL internal network traffic using the subordinate certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In 2012, the Flame malware (also known as SkyWiper) contained modules that had an MD5 collision with a valid certificate issued by a Microsoft Terminal Server licensing certificate that used the broken MD5 hash algorithm.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The authors thus was able to conduct a collision attack with the hash listed in the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] In 2015, a Chinese certificate authority named MCS Holdings and affiliated with China's central domain registry issued unauthorized certificates for Google domains.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Google thus removed both MCS and the root certificate authority from Chrome and have revoked the certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] An attacker who steals a certificate authority's private keys is able to forge certificates as if they were CA, without needed ongoing access to the CA's systems.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Key theft is therefore one of the main risks certificate authorities defend against.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Publicly trusted CAs almost always store their keys on a hardware security module (HSM), which allows them to sign certificates with a key, but generally prevent extraction of that key with both physical and software controls.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] CAs typically take the further precaution of keeping the key for their long-term root certificates in an HSM that is kept offline, except when it is needed to sign shorter-lived intermediate certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The intermediate certificates, stored in an online HSM, can do the day-to-day work of signing end-entity certificates and keeping revocation information up to date.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] CAs sometimes use a key ceremony when generating signing keys, in order to ensure that the keys are not tampered with or copied.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The critical weakness in the way that the current X.509 scheme is implemented is that any CA trusted by a particular party can then issue certificates for any domain they choose.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Such certificates will be accepted as valid by the trusting party whether they are legitimate and authorized or not.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This is a serious shortcoming given that the most commonly encountered technology employing X.509 and trusted third parties is the HTTPS protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] As all major web browsers are distributed to their end-users pre-configured with a list of trusted CAs that numbers in the dozens this means that any one of these pre-approved trusted CAs can issue a valid certificate for any domain whatsoever.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] The industry response to this has been muted.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] Given that the contents of a browser's pre-configured trusted CA list is determined independently by the party that is distributing or causing to be installed the browser application there is really nothing that the CAs themselves can do.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] This issue is the driving impetus behind the development of the DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/certificate-authority] If adopted in conjunction with Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) DANE will greatly reduce if not eliminate the role of trusted third parties in a domain's PKI.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] A **domain validated certificate** (**DV**) is an X.509 public key certificate typically used for Transport Layer Security (TLS) where the domain name of the applicant is validated by proving some control over a DNS domain.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] Domain validated certificates were first distributed by GeoTrust in 2002 before becoming a widely accepted method.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] The sole criterion for a domain validated certificate is proof of control over whois records, DNS records file, email or web hosting account of a domain.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] A domain validated certificate is distinct from an Extended Validation Certificate in that this is the only requirement for issuing the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] In particular, domain validated certificates do not assure that any particular legal entity is connected to the certificate, even if the domain name may imply a particular legal entity controls the domain.
[src:acme-protocol/domain-validation] As of 2020, all major browsers user interfaces display EV, OV, and DV certificates identically, but provide options to query the type of certificate via multiple clicks.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The mission of the organization is to create a more secure and privacy-respecting World Wide Web by promoting the widespread adoption of HTTPS.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt certificates are valid for 90 days by default, during which renewal can take place at any time.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Optionally, certificates can be issued which are valid for 45 days (tlsserver profile) and 6 days (shortlived profile).
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] This is handled by an automated process designed to overcome manual creation, validation, signing, installation, and renewal of certificates for secure websites.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The project claims its goal is to make encrypted connections to World Wide Web servers ubiquitous.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] By eliminating payment, web server configuration, validation email management and certificate renewal tasks, it is meant to significantly lower the complexity of setting up and maintaining TLS encryption.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On a Linux web server, execution of only two commands is sufficient to set up HTTPS encryption and acquire and install certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] To that end, a software package was included into the official Debian and Ubuntu software repositories.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Current initiatives of major browser developers such as Mozilla and Google to deprecate unencrypted HTTP are counting on the availability of Let's Encrypt.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The project is acknowledged to have the potential to accomplish encrypted connections as the default case for the entire Web.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The service only issues domain-validated certificates, since they can be fully automated.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Organization Validation and Extended Validation Certificates both require human validation of any registrants, and are therefore not offered by Let's Encrypt.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Support of ACME v2 and wildcard certificates was added in March 2018.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The domain validation (DV) utilized by Let's Encrypt dates back to 2002 and was at first controversial when introduced by GeoTrust before becoming a widely accepted method for the issuance of SSL certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] By being as transparent as possible, the organization hopes to both protect its own trustworthiness and guard against attacks and manipulation attempts.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] For that purpose it regularly publishes transparency reports, publicly logs all ACME transactions (e.g. by using Certificate Transparency), and uses open standards and free software as much as possible.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The Let's Encrypt project was started in 2012 by two Mozilla employees, Josh Aas and Eric Rescorla, together with Peter Eckersley at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and J.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Alex Halderman at the University of Michigan.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Internet Security Research Group, the company behind Let's Encrypt, was incorporated in May 2013.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt was announced publicly on November 18, 2014.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On January 28, 2015, the ACME protocol was officially submitted to the IETF for standardization.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On April 9, 2015, the ISRG and the Linux Foundation declared their collaboration.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The root and intermediate certificates were generated in the beginning of June.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On June 16, 2015, the final launch schedule for the service was announced, with the first certificate expected to be issued sometime in the week of July 27, 2015, followed by a limited issuance period to test security and scalability.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] General availability of the service was originally planned to begin sometime in the week of September 14, 2015.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On August 7, 2015, the launch schedule was amended to provide more time for ensuring system security and stability, with the first certificate to be issued in the week of September 7, 2015 followed by general availability in the week of November 16, 2015.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On September 14, 2015, Let's Encrypt issued its first certificate, which was for the domain helloworld.letsencrypt.org.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On the same day, ISRG submitted its root program applications to Mozilla, Microsoft, Google and Apple.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On October 19, 2015, the intermediate certificates became cross-signed by IdenTrust, causing all certificates issued by Let's Encrypt to be trusted by all major browsers.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On November 12, 2015, Let's Encrypt announced that general availability would be pushed back and that the first public beta would commence on December 3, 2015.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The public beta ran from December 3, 2015 to April 12, 2016.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On March 3, 2020, Let's Encrypt announced that it would have to revoke over 3 million certificates on March 4, due to a flaw in its Certificate Authority software.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Through working with software vendors and contacting site operators, Let's Encrypt was able to get 1.7 million of the affected certificates renewed before the deadline.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] They ultimately decided not to revoke the remaining affected certificates, as the security risk was low and the certificates were to expire within the next 90 days.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The mass-revocation event has significantly increased the global revocation rate.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] In March 2020, Let's Encrypt was awarded the Free Software Foundation's annual Award for Projects of Social Benefit.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On February 27, 2020, Let's Encrypt announced having issued a billion certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] In April 2022, Let's Encrypt was awarded the Levchin Prize for “fundamental improvements to the certificate ecosystem that provide free certificates for all”.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] As of 2025, Let's Encrypt serves more than 700 million websites worldwide, making it the largest certificate authority in the world.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] In January 2025, Let's Encrypt announced the retirement of its free email expiry notifications and recommended Red Sift Certificates Lite as its certificate monitoring service.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] In June 2015, Let's Encrypt announced the generation of their first RSA root certificate, ISRG Root X1.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The root certificate was used to sign two intermediate certificates, which are also cross-signed by the certificate authority IdenTrust.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] One of the intermediate certificates is used to sign issued certificates, while the other is kept offline as a backup in case of problems with the first intermediate certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Because the IdenTrust certificate was already widely trusted by major web browsers, Let's Encrypt certificates can normally be validated and accepted by relying parties even before browser vendors include the ISRG root certificate as a trust anchor.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt developers planned to generate an ECDSA root key back in 2015, but then pushed back the plan to early 2016, then to 2019, and finally to 2020.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] On September 3, 2020, Let's Encrypt issued six new certificates: one new ECDSA root named "ISRG Root X2", four intermediates, and one cross-sign.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The new ISRG Root X2 is cross-signed with ISRG Root X1, Let's Encrypt's own root certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt did not issue an OCSP responder for the new intermediate certificates and instead plans to rely solely on certificate revocation lists (CRLs) to recall compromised certificates and short validity periods to reduce danger of certificate compromise.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The challenge–response protocol used to automate enrolling with the certificate authority is called Automatic Certificate Management Environment (ACME).
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] It can query either Web servers or DNS servers controlled by the domain covered by the certificate to be issued.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Based on whether the resulting responses match the expectations, control of the enrollee over the domain is assured (domain validation).
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The ACME client software can set up a dedicated TLS server that gets queried by the ACME certificate authority server with requests using Server Name Indication (Domain Validation using Server Name Indication, DVSNI), or it can use hooks to publish responses to existing Web and DNS servers.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The validation processes are run multiple times over separate network paths.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Checking whether DNS entries are provisioned is done from multiple geographically diverse locations to make DNS spoofing attacks harder to carry out.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] ACME interactions are based on exchanging JSON documents over HTTPS connections.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The specification developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) is a proposed standard, RFC 8555.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Prior to the completion and publication of RFC 8555, Let's Encrypt implemented a pre-standard draft of the ACME protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] RFC 8555 introduced breaking changes and as such it has been dubbed ACMEv2.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt implemented the new version and started pushing existing clients into upgrades.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The nudging was implemented with intermittent down-times of the ACMEv1 API.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The end-of-lifetime was announced with dates and phases in "End of Life Plan for ACMEv1".
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Since November 8, 2019, ACMEv1 no longer accepts new account registrations.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Since June 2020, ACMEv1 stopped accepting new domain validations.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] From January 2021, ACMEv1 underwent 24-hour brownouts.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The ACMEv1 API was turned off completely on June 1, 2021.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The certificate authority consists of a piece of software called Boulder, written in Go, that implements the server side of the ACME protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] It is published as free software with source code under the terms of version 2 of the Mozilla Public License (MPL).
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] It provides a RESTful API that can be accessed over a TLS-encrypted channel.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] An Apache-licensed Python certificate management program called *certbot* (formerly *letsencrypt*) gets installed on the client side (the Web server of an enrollee).
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] This is used to order the certificate, to conduct the domain validation process, to install the certificate, to configure the HTTPS encryption in the HTTP server, and later to regularly renew the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] After installation and agreeing to the user license, executing a single command is enough to get a valid certificate installed.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Additional options like OCSP stapling or HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) can also be enabled.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Automatic setup initially only works with Apache and nginx.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt issues certificates valid for 90 days.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] The reason given is that these certificates "limit damage from key compromise and mis-issuance" and encourage automation.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] Initially, Let's Encrypt developed its own ACME client – Certbot – as an official implementation.
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] This has been transferred to Electronic Frontier Foundation and its name "letsencrypt" has been changed to "certbot".
[src:acme-protocol/let-s-encrypt] There is a large selection of ACME clients and projects for a number of environments developed by the community.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:acme-protocol/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:acme-protocol/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
